Here's the complete migration with the critical pitfalls explained:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

```csharp
// ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // ── CSV Export ──────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Response.Clear/Write/End/AddHeader are all gone.
    // Use IActionResult return types — the framework handles headers & streaming.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);

        // File() sets Content-Disposition and Content-Type for you
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // ── Redirect ───────────────────────────────────────────────
    // Response.Redirect(url, endResponse: true) used Thread.Abort to halt
    // execution mid-pipeline. That entire pattern is gone.
    // Return RedirectResult instead — nothing after "return" executes.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");  // returns immediately, no Thread.Abort
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ⚠️ DO NOT catch ThreadAbortException — it no longer exists in
        // .NET Core. Remove all catch blocks for it.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| # | .NET Framework Pattern | Why It Breaks in Core | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Response.End()` | Threw `ThreadAbortException` to halt the pipeline. Removed entirely — no equivalent exists. | Return an `IActionResult` |
| 2 | `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | The `endResponse` param called `Thread.Abort()`. Thread aborting is **not supported** in .NET Core and throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. | Return `Redirect()` / `RedirectResult` |
| 3 | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ThreadAbortException` doesn't exist in the Core runtime. Code catching it will never trigger — but worse, it masks the removal of the redirect-abort pattern. | Delete these catch blocks entirely |
| 4 | `Response.Write(data)` | `HttpResponse.Write` doesn't exist. `Body` is a raw `Stream`. | Return `File()`, `Content()`, or write to `Response.Body` |
| 5 | `Response.AddHeader()` | Removed. Headers API changed. | Use `Response.Headers.Append()` or let `File()` handle it |
| 6 | `Response.Clear()` | Removed. Responses aren't buffered the same way. | Not needed — action results compose the full response |

## The Fundamental Shift

```
ASP.NET Framework (imperative):
  ➜ Mutate Response object in-place, call End() to flush

ASP.NET Core (declarative):
  ➜ Return an IActionResult — the framework writes the response
```

In Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` literally called `Thread.Abort()` to prevent any code after it from running. In Core, **you control flow with normal `return` statements**. If you port code that had logic *after* a redirect call relying on the abort to skip it, that code **will now execute** — audit carefully.

## If You Need Streaming (Large Files)

```csharp
[HttpGet]
public async Task ExportLargeReport()
{
    Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
    Response.Headers.Append("Content-Disposition",
        "attachment; filename=report.csv");

    await using var writer = new StreamWriter(Response.Body);
    await foreach (var line in GenerateReportLinesAsync())
    {
        await writer.WriteLineAsync(line);
        await writer.FlushAsync();   // streams chunks to client
    }
}
```

The core rule: **stop mutating `Response` imperatively — return result objects and let the framework own the HTTP response lifecycle.**
